    <body>
      <entry xml:id="entry_7rx0ym" xml:lang="os" abv:completeness="english-questions">
        <form type="lemma" xml:lang="os-x-iron"><orth>ᵆrxₒym</orth></form>
        <form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal"><orth>ærxun</orth></form>
        <sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
              <q>печальный</q>
            </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
              <q>sad</q>
            </abv:tr></sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
              <q>грустный</q>
            </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
              <q>sorrowful</q>
            </abv:tr></sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
              <q>удрученный</q>
            </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
              <q>depressed</q>
            </abv:tr></sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
              <q>печаль</q>
            </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
              <q>sadness</q>
            </abv:tr></sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
              <q>тоска</q>
            </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
              <q>depression</q>
            </abv:tr></sense></sense>
        <note xml:lang="ru" type="comment">; в иронском очень редко; близки по значению <ref
            type="xr" target="#entry_ænkʼard"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_7rxændæg"/>, <ref
            type="xr" target="#entry_mætʼæl"/></note>
        <note xml:lang="en" type="comment">; rarely used in Iron; words <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_ænkʼard"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_7rxændæg"/>, <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_mætʼæl"/> are close in meaning</note>
        <exampleGrp xmlns="http://ossetic-studies.org/ns/abaevdict">
          <example>
            <quote xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">wæ, næ mad, <oRef>ærx˳ymæj</oRef> та
              bad!</quote>
            <tr xml:lang="ru">
              <q xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">о наша мать, не сиди печальная!</q>
            </tr>
            <tr xml:lang="en">
              <q xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Oh, our mother, don't sit sad!</q>
            </tr>
            <bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><ref type="bibl" target="#src_MD"/>
              <biblScope>1965 IX 5</biblScope></bibl>
          </example>
          <example xml:lang="os-x-digor">
            <usg xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><lang/></usg>
            <quote xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">ci ungæg dæn ci те
              <oRef>ʽrxunæj</oRef>!</quote>
            <tr xml:lang="ru">
              <q xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">как мне тяжело (<q>тесно</q>) в моей тоске!</q>
            </tr>
            <tr xml:lang="en">
              <q xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">how hard (<q>cramped</q>) it is for me in my
                anguish!</q>
            </tr>
            <bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Iræf"/>
              <biblScope>22</biblScope></bibl>
          </example>
          <example xml:lang="os-x-digor">
            <usg xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><lang/></usg>
            <quote xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><oRef>ærxunbadæ</oRef> kænuj</quote>
            <tr xml:lang="ru">
              <q xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">он сидит удрученный</q>
            </tr>
            <tr xml:lang="en">
              <q xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">He is sitting there depressed</q>
            </tr>
          </example>
        </exampleGrp>
        <etym xml:lang="ru">Формально могла бы соблазнить безупречная близость к <mentioned
            xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
            <w>xrūma-</w>
            <gloss><q>кровавый</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>страшный</q></gloss></mentioned>, но значения
          слишком далеки. Скорее следует поставить в связь с <ref type="xr" target="#entry_7rxændæg"
              ><w>ᵆrxændæg</w>
            <gloss><q>печальный</q></gloss></ref> и пр. Если в <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_7rxændæg"/> распознается <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec"
              >granta-</w></mentioned>, т. е. причастие от <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec"
              >gram-</w>
            <gloss><q>сердиться</q></gloss></mentioned> и пр., то <oRef>ᵆrxₒym</oRef> можно
          возводить к глагольному имени <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec"
            >grama-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ine"><lang/>
            <w type="rec">ghromo-</w></mentioned>, представленному в <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
            <w>γaram</w>
            <gloss><q>гнев</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>раздражение</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="fa"><w>γarmān</w>, <w>γarmanda</w>
            <gloss><q>гневный</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>раздраженный</q></gloss></mentioned> и в ряде
          германских фактов: <mentioned xml:lang="ang" extralang="goh"><lang/>
            <w>gram</w>
            <gloss><q>находящийся в дурном настроении</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="goh"><lang/>
            <w>gramiz</w>
            <gloss><q>печальный</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>мрачный</q></gloss>,
              <gloss><q>сердитый</q></gloss></mentioned> и т. д. Звуковое развитие <mentioned
            xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec">grama-</w></mentioned> → <oRef>ᵆrxₒym</oRef> представляется
          закономерным. Индоевропейский звонкий придыхательный <c>gh</c> отразился в осетинском на
          этот раз как глухой фрикатив <c>x</c>. Полную аналогию этому дают случаи развития и.е.
            <c>bh-</c> → ос. <c>f</c>. Как из <mentioned xml:lang="ine"><w type="rec"
            >bhruko-</w></mentioned> имеем <ref type="xr" target="#entry_7rfyg" xml:lang="os"><lang/>
            <w><?oxy_comment_start author="Irene" timestamp="20220406T142804+0300" comment="почему не rfyg? и дальше не rxym"?>rfug<?oxy_comment_end?></w>
            <gloss><q>бровь</q></gloss></ref>, так из <mentioned xml:lang="ine"><w type="rec"
              >ghromo-</w></mentioned> ос. <oRef>rxum</oRef>. Переход <c>a</c> → <c>y</c> | <c>u</c>
          в соседстве с <c>m</c> наблюдается и в других случаях: <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_dymyn"><w xml:lang="os-x-iron">dymyn</w><w xml:lang="os-x-digor"
              >dumun</w>
            <gloss><q>дуть</q></gloss></ref> из <mentioned xml:lang="ira"
              ><?oxy_comment_start author="Irene" timestamp="20220406T142940+0300" comment="здесь и далее иран.?"?><w
              type="rec">dam-</w><?oxy_comment_end?></mentioned>, <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_cymyn"><w xml:lang="os-x-iron">cymyn</w><w xml:lang="os-x-digor"
              >cumun</w>
            <gloss><q>хлебать</q></gloss></ref> из <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec"
            >čam-</w></mentioned>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_myd"><w xml:lang="os-x-iron"
              >myd</w><w xml:lang="os-x-digor">mud</w>
            <gloss><q>мед</q></gloss></ref> из <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec"
            >madu-</w></mentioned>. Дигорский дает в исходе <c>n</c> вместо <c>m</c>, как обычно
              (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/>
            <biblScope>378–379</biblScope></bibl>). Еще одна возможность: возведение к <mentioned
            xml:lang="ine"><lang/>
            <w type="rec">kru-</w>
            <note xml:lang="ru" type="comment">с исходным значением</note>
            <gloss><q>стыть</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>коченеть</q></gloss><note xml:lang="en"
              type="comment">с исходным значением <gloss><q>стыть</q></gloss>,
                  <gloss><q>коченеть</q></gloss></note></mentioned>; ср. <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
            <w>κρυμός</w>
            <gloss><q>стужа</q></gloss></mentioned>, а в переносном значении <mentioned
            xml:lang="ang"><lang/>
            <w>hrēow</w>
            <gloss><q>сожаление</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>грусть</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="ang"><w>hrēowan</w>
            <gloss><q>печалить</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>огорчать</q></gloss>
            <note xml:lang="ru" type="comment">и пр. (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Falk-Torp"/>
                <biblScope>II 917</biblScope></bibl>)</note><note xml:lang="en" type="comment">и пр.
                  (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Falk-Torp"/>
                <biblScope>II 917</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>. — Ср. <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_7rxændæg"/>.</etym>
        <etym xml:lang="en">Formally, an impeccable proximity to <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
            <w>xrūma-</w>
            <gloss><q>bloody</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>terrible</q></gloss></mentioned> seems enticing,
          but the meanings are too different. Rather, it should be put in connection with <ref
            type="xr" target="#entry_7rxændæg"><w>ᵆrxændæg</w>
            <gloss><q>sad</q></gloss></ref> etc. If in <ref type="xr" target="#entry_7rxændæg"/>
          there is <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec">granta-</w></mentioned>, i. e. a
          participle form of <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec">gram-</w>
            <gloss><q>be angry</q></gloss></mentioned> etc., then <oRef>ᵆrxₒym</oRef> could be
          traced back to a deverbal noun <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec"
            >grama-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ine"><lang/>
            <w type="rec">ghromo-</w></mentioned>, present in <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
            <w>γaram</w>
            <gloss><q>anger</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>irritation</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="fa"><w>γarmān</w>, <w>γarmanda</w>
            <gloss><q>angry</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>irritated</q></gloss></mentioned> and in a number
          of German words: <mentioned xml:lang="ang" extralang="goh"><lang/>
            <w>gram</w>
            <gloss><q>being in a bad mood</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="goh"><lang/>
            <w>gramiz</w>
            <gloss><q>sad</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>gloomy</q></gloss>,
            <gloss><q>angry</q></gloss></mentioned> etc. The sound development <mentioned
            xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec">grama-</w></mentioned> → <oRef>ᵆrxₒym</oRef> seems regular.
          In this case an Indo-European voiced aspirated sound <c>gh</c> reflected in Ossetic as a
          voiceless fricative <c>x</c>. A complete analogy to this is given by the cases of
          development Indo-European <c>bh-</c> → Ossetic <c>f</c>. The same way as <mentioned
            xml:lang="ine"><w type="rec">bhruko-</w></mentioned>
          <?oxy_comment_start author="Irene" timestamp="20220531T112742+0300" comment="?"?>led<?oxy_comment_end?>
          to <ref type="xr" target="#entry_7rfyg" xml:lang="os"><lang/>
            <w>rfug</w>
            <gloss><q>eyebrow</q></gloss></ref>, <mentioned xml:lang="ine"><w type="rec"
            >ghromo-</w></mentioned> led to Ossetic <oRef>rxum</oRef>. The change <c>a</c> →
            <c>y</c> | <c>u</c> near <c>m</c> is also present in other cases: <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_dymyn"><w xml:lang="os-x-iron">dymyn</w><w xml:lang="os-x-digor"
              >dumun</w>
            <gloss><q>blow</q></gloss></ref> from <mentioned xml:lang="ira"
              ><?oxy_comment_start author="Irene" timestamp="20220406T142940+0300" comment="здесь и далее иран.?"?><w
              type="rec">dam-</w><?oxy_comment_end?></mentioned>, <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_cymyn"><w xml:lang="os-x-iron">cymyn</w><w xml:lang="os-x-digor"
              >cumun</w>
            <gloss><q>slurp</q></gloss></ref> from <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec"
            >čam-</w></mentioned>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_myd"><w xml:lang="os-x-iron"
              >myd</w><w xml:lang="os-x-digor">mud</w>
            <gloss><q>honey</q></gloss></ref> from <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><w type="rec"
            >madu-</w></mentioned>. Digor has <c>n</c> instead of <c>m</c>, as usual (<bibl><ref
              type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/>
            <biblScope>378–379</biblScope></bibl>). There is another possibility: to trace back to
            <mentioned xml:lang="ine"><lang/>
            <w type="rec">kru-</w>
            <note xml:lang="ru" type="comment">с исходным значением <gloss><q>стыть</q></gloss>,
                  <gloss><q>коченеть</q></gloss></note><note xml:lang="en" type="comment">with the
              initial meaning</note>
            <gloss><q>get cold</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>stiffen</q></gloss></mentioned>; cf.
            <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
            <w>κρυμός</w>
            <gloss><q>icy cold</q></gloss></mentioned>, and metaforically <mentioned xml:lang="ang"><lang/>
            <w>hrēow</w>
            <gloss><q>regret</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>sadness</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="ang"><w>hrēowan</w>
            <gloss><q>sadden</q></gloss>, <gloss><q>upset</q></gloss>
            <note xml:lang="ru" type="comment">и пр. (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Falk-Torp"/>
                <biblScope>II 917</biblScope></bibl>)</note><note xml:lang="en" type="comment">etc.
                  (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Falk-Torp"/>
                <biblScope>II 917</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>. — Cf. <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_7rxændæg"/>.</etym>
      </entry>
